False . Fat stores far more calories per unit volume than carbohydrates . Carbohydrate molecules are , by definition , already half oxidized ( oxidation is the process which releases energy for the body to use , so being half oxidized means there's less stored for future use ) . That's why our bodies use glycogen ( a carbohydrate ) for short-term storage ( primarily for the overnight fast as we sleep ) , but fat for long-term storage . Our bodies would have to be much larger to contain enough carbohydrates to store the same amount of energy as our fat stores . I'm not an expert either – I only have an undergraduate degree so far . But biology is a science , and scientific facts are determined by careful study and experimentation , not by speculation about uncontrolled personal experience . If you've found a weight loss method that works for you ( and a weight maintenance method for when you reach your goal – that's where many people fail ) , great , congrats . But that doesn't mean that the explanations you invent for why it's working for you are accurate , or will lead to the same results for others .

Paywall so Poland triggered a showdown between eastern and western Europe yesterday when its MPs voted to give parliament the power to appoint supreme court judges , despite the threat of sanctions from Brussels . The European Commission had warned that the legislation would undermine the separation of judicial and political powers , seen as a cornerstone of democracy and the rule of law . On Wednesday it gave Poland a week to rethink the plans and to avoid sanctions : the suspension of its full EU membership by the withdrawal of its voting rights , a measure that has never been used against a member state . Thousands of people protested against the legislation in Warsaw yesterday , many waving EU flags This enraged the Polish government , which yesterday won the backing of Hungary to resist European officials . Tensions have been running high in some of the former communist nations , which are resisting the EU ’ s insistence that every member state must take a share of refugees . The latest dispute began when Poland ’ s ruling Law and Justice Party rushed through a bill proposed only last week to give the justice minister the power to appoint judges to the supreme court . Further powers for the minister to organise the work of the court and decide which judges should remain were switched to the president under an amendment last night designed to make it more palatable to Brussels . The bill quickly followed one that was approved last week , giving parliament control over the National Council of the Judiciary . Jaroslaw Kaczynski , leader of Law and Justice party , sits at the centre of the front row as his party votes to pass the controversial measureJaroslaw Kaczynski , leader of Law and Justice party , sits at the centre of the front row as his party votes to pass the controversial measure “ Collectively , they would abolish any remaining judicial independence and put the judiciary under full political control of the government , ” Frans Timmermans , vice-president of the commission , said , adding that the changes would “ considerably increase the systemic threat to the rule of law ” . Polish MPs voted by <NUMBER> to <NUMBER> , with <NUMBER> abstentions , to pass the bill and send it to the upper house today , where it is certain to pass thanks to the Law and Justice Party ’ s majority there . The final step to becoming law will be the signature of President Duda , a lawyer who used to be a Law and Justice MP , but who ran as an independent for the presidency in <NUMBER> . Crowds gathered in Warsaw last night calling for him to veto the bill . Donald Tusk , the former prime minister of Poland who is now president of the European Council , called for a solution to a “ very serious situation ” . He said that he has proposed a meeting with Mr Duda to try to avoid “ bleak outcomes which could ultimately lead to the marginalisation of Poland in Europe ” . He added : “ They transport us , in the political sense , in time and in space backwards and eastwards and ruin an already tarnished public opinion of Polish democracy . ” Mr Duda ’ s office said the president had rejected the offer of a meeting with Mr Tusk . During yesterday ’ s debate , Adam Bodnar , Poland ’ s human rights ombudsman , told parliament that the legislation would “ deprive citizens of the right to an independent court ” , adding : “ We are planting an explosive under our judiciary . ” Law and Justice said that it wanted to shake up the top court because it had become a “ state within a state ” and lacked accountability . It was heavily criticised for making political appointments to the constitutional court in <NUMBER> , but escaped EU censure . Jaroslaw Kaczynski , chairman of the party , said that “ far-reaching , radical actions ” were required because the judiciary had not been reformed since communist times and was inefficient . Opposition politicians , judges and European officials criticised the vote . Grzegorz Schetyna , head of Civic Platform , the main opposition party , denounced the bill as an “ announcement of a coup ” . Malgorzata Gersdorf , president of the supreme court , said that the bill would transform it into a “ court attached to the justice ministry ” . She added : “ This is very dangerous for the political system we are living in . ” Krystian Markiewicz , president of Iustitia , the Polish judges ’ association , also described the proposed change to the law as a “ coup ” . “ The rule of law and democracy are ending , the independence of powers is over , ” Mr Markiewicz said . “ The minister will appoint the judges that he favours . ” He added that the measure was introduced “ at night , completely out of the blue , with no social consultation ” and “ does not fit into EU standards ” . Hungary said that it stood by Poland and warned the commission not to meddle in Poland ’ s internal affairs . Peter Szijjarto , the Hungarian foreign minister , added : “ We stand by Poland and we call on the European Commission not to overstep its authority . ” Mr Timmermans said on Wednesday that the commission could invoke Article <NUMBER> of the EU treaties , which could lead to voting rights in the Council of the European Union being suspended . The article was set up to hold countries accountable for human rights violations , but the ultimate step of suspension would require unanimity , with Hungary unlikely to support the move . I am a National Socialist , and I'd be happy to explain what that means . National Socialism is a bit of a misnomer since it was used during a time Socialism could refer to any ideology that appeals to the interests of the workers , while not necessarily being a Pro-class struggle or Communist ideology . It would be more accurate to call National Socialism a Corporatist ideology . Like other forms of Fascism , National Socialism advocates for a system that protects private property and allows for a market economy , but the State promotes and ensures that there is class unity as opposed to class struggle , healthy class relations that are beneficial for all involved . NS is in favor of Nationalism and ethnocentrism . We believes that every nation's and every race's autonomy should be preserved . This doesn't mean every nation is isolated from each other , but National Socialism is against globalism and globalization . Foreigners are allowed to exist within a NS nation , but they have to respect the society they are in and follow the law of foreigners . The interests of the nation and society are held deeply . We advocate for a one-party meritocratic government that chooses and promotes leaders based on their competence and gives them accountability proportionate to the power they hold . National Socialism opposes the Liberal concept of democracy , but this does not mean we're against all forms of voting and other citizen participation in government . The Third Reich itself held multiple plebiscites and citizens were empowered to become involved in their communities . Society in general will be built around meritocracy . The amount of effort and good you produce will determine what you get from society . There will be incentives for people to improve their bodies , their minds , and their communities . There will be incentives for those who benefit their communities , and their nation directly or indirectly . These incentives will likely come in the form of access to additional social services and other benefits . Aside from that , there are many different interpretations of National Socialism . If you have any questions , feel free to ask me . I'll even suggest you some additional reading if you want more in-depth perspectives related to National Socialism . Let me know if you need more recommendations . Suggested Reading - Mein Kampf by Adolf Hitler This is mostly a biographical look at Hitler's life and his political views , it's a long read and is in a conversational tone that may be hard to read . However , it may help you understand Adolf Hitler a little more . The Programme of the NSDAP by Gottfried Feder This is a good book for the actual politics of the NSDAP . It outlines the social , political , and economic foundation of National Socialism in Germany . I highly recommend it . White Power by George Lincoln Rockwell This is a good book for learning about Rockwell's post-war interpretation of National Socialism and is a decent introduction to the American strain of NS in general . National Socialism : Vanguard of the Future by Colin Jordan . This is another book written after World War II and the subsequent fall of the German Reich . It's a collection of several essays on the topic of Germany and National Socialism . Who We Are by William Luther Pierce Another good piece of literature on the topic of National Socialism , in general I'd recommend Pierce's work . He sometimes goes under the pen name Andrew Macdonald , so just be aware of that .

By router , I meant your WiFi router . If you have a separate WiFi Access point and then a router to the internet , that changes the possible nature of the problem . Great signal , but still losing a significant numbers of packets . That's a bit wonky . Anyway , now you know a bit more about where the problem lies . Try forcing the bit rate to a lower value . It's possible that , for some reason , it's constantly re-negotiating a rate because it's on auto , trying the best speed , failing and falling back . Try " iwconfig wlan 0 rate 27M auto " to give it an upper limit , which often helps on congested airspaces . Some WiFi card drivers deal a lot better than others with congestion . If that's the case , maybe you could switch your router's frequency to a less used channel ( have a look with wpa_gui , scan ) . In the iwconfig output , do you see the number " Tx excessive retries " going up often ? That's another sign .

I don't think ideology is really the problem . It's more structural , the realities and necessities of power . Ideology serves only as rationale , justification , rhetorical cover as people who seek power , or seek to hold on to it , implement policies that are of benefit to the rich , influential , the powerful - those who can help the attain power or hold on to it - but that achieve results that are exactly the opposite of what their purported ideology aimed for . Liberals and progressives hate libertarianism because Republicans specialize in using it as rhetorical cover , while implementing corporatist BS . Yet the problem isn't with Libertarianism per se - the same can be done with Socialism . See e . g . USSR and Maoist China . This is the lesson of Animal Farm . Those who are convinced capitalism / free market ideology are the problem should do well to understand , Socialism too is prone to being hijacked and coopted , and used to do great evil . So maybe the thing to do is not fight at the ideology level , but try to improve people's understanding of the political system . It flabbergasts me that so many otherwise intelligent progressives are absolutely convinced that if they cast a vote for Ron Paul , they'll magically morph into heartless greedy libertarians , or the American Ruling Class will somehow turn more libertarian in economic ideology , or something . They remind me of Christian fundie nutters who are convinced that if we stop mass-murdering Arabs , or funding Israel , next thing you know we'll be under occupation by Islamic Caliphate troops who will impose Sharia on us . System runs on hate and loathing - liberals and progressives need to be made to understand that this shit works just as well on them , as it does on RedState Rural Redneck Cons .

I agree . It is important to make the setup and use of VOIP as simple as possible to maximize its adoption within the game and that can be challenging . However , I'd say that games like MMOs , such as WoW , lend themselves towards the use text chat and private VOIP servers . Back when I played WoW , I rarely wanted to talk to a random player and if I did , the gameplay provided me with ample time to type out complex messages . With members of a guild , that was different ; voice became an integral part of socializing and coordinating raids , etc . For team FPS games , I often want to tell a random player something and the fast-paced gameplay makes it impossible to type out complex messages ( unless I'm staring at the spawn screen ) . Being able to bark out a warning or order to another player , even if it's unidirectional because the other player hasn't bothered to set up VOIP , is beneficial to gameplay , in my opinion .

Some heroin is so supplemented with other ( dangerous ) stuff that the user barely gets high ; and some is so powerful it will kill the user . Not knowing the potency of the drug is what leads to many overdoses . There are also the many longer term health effects of intravenous heroin use , often caused by sharing needles and using poor venipunture technique . I never said " modern " leftist . You did . You falsely attributed that to me , called it wrong thus creating a principle for consistency , and then immediately ignored that very principle thus being logically inconsistent . You yourself claimed that I was wrong by claiming that I attributed modern leftism to the founding fathers ( and that this isn't accurately descriptive ) , then you yourself attributed modern Libertarianism to the founding fathers . The founding fathers were mostly leftists by virtue of being left of center . Many of the features of their ideology and the tenets in their writings are still leftist , and were mostly leftist for the time period . Those Libertarian features you are seeing ? Those were left of center in <NUMBER> . I . e . , leftist . Many ideals you would consider conservative today were leftist then . As you yourself said , modern leftism has changed . I don't think you realized how , because only one of your examples encompasses a minority of leftist ideologies ( " pro-socialist policies " ) . And , believe it or not , expanding the role of federal government into people's lives is also a very Fascist belief , with the understanding that people are naturally irrational and need government control . Fascism is very , very conservative , yet it's also leftist ? You're also taking a very naive view of conservativism . These aren't just political ideologies ; you can't compare conservatism's social aspects to liberalism's financial aspects , for example , and call it an accurate comparison . Conservatives ( of which Liberatarians are a part of , not a complimentary group or some such nonsense like you seem to think ) care very much about morality , as does literally every other person , everywhere . Modern conservatives care about the Constitution , but the ideas the ideology is founded on existed long before the Constitution . Protection of minority rights from majority rule is the single most basic tenet of conservatism , contrasted with the leftist idea of supporting the majority . Realism ( vs idealism ) , and traditionalism are other basic and so far unchanged tenets . Would you call the founding fathers realists ? Traditionalists ? Did they protect the minority opinion from the majority ? You could say they did in the sense that they wanted religious freedom , and then say they didn't in the sense that itself was a majority opinion . Traditionalism has resulted in different features in different cultures too ; for example , liberal economics are seen as conservative in the U . S . because the U . S . was originally and traditionally liberal economically . Christian moral theory and adherence to the constitution are features of U . S . conservatives due to tradition as well . Some features that are attributed to conservatives are really just conservative political parties taking opposing sides on issues to spite other parties ; gun control is both a far left and far right policy , for similar reasons : an armed populace is tough to oppress . So , to sum it up , you only gave a single leftist tenet in your examples , and that suffers from the same problem as we had before : modern Socialism isn't the same as it was when it was in its infancy , right around the time of the revolution . At the time it was the belief that there needs to be some minimum level of control over mercantilism , precursor to modern capitalism . As the majority of the founding fathers were Federalists , they can be said to have supported similar ideas though I do not know if they were explicitly aware of the existence of Socialism . While not declaring whether they ( the Federalist Party ) were primarily left or right , they were supportive of a mercantile economy as an alternative to the existing plantation-based economy , but they also supported the idea of a strong federal government so that states wouldn't be forced to individually deal with their own or other states ' problems ( and economic bullshit ) . Starting to sound less like the ideology you know and love ? Actually , this polarization we see today didn't even become a thing until the mid-twentieth century . Party loyalty was nearly nonexistent , and parties weren't measured on a right-left axis outside adademia . But something you should note is that today's liberals become tomorrow's conservatives . Your views were once further left than they currently are , because leftists love change and conservatives hate it . I'm deliberately using " leftist " instead of " liberal " for most of this too , because while liberals are leftist , leftists aren't necessarily liberal and there are some very distinct and disturbing non-liberal ideologues in leftism . I personally believe the right-left axis , or newer double axis , isn't adequate to measure the difference in direction of most ideals anymore , as Social Justice Theory is no friend of Liberalism .

I don't like the attempts to vindicate atheism by saying " nah , just communism . " Whether or not the government controls the economy is largely irrelevant to whether it enforces a given religious viewpoint by force . It would be possible to have a theocratic communist state , or a capitalist or corporatist state advancing atheism through force . What matters here is that Stalin , inheriting the political legacy of Marx , used state violence to advance atheism because he believed ( or at the very least pretended to believe ) atheism to be correct and preferable as a religious viewpoint . My response to the OP , again , is that we should concede that it is possible to commit atrocities out of a belief in the merits of atheism , but argue that religion - in so far as it posits the existence of a judgemental deity and an eternal soul - makes it easier to justify atrocities by ' raising the stakes ' . That is to say , it is easier to justify the massacre of thousands on the basis that fewer souls will be tormented for eternity than to justify the same on the basis of concrete policy rationale . The argument that Stalin wasn't really concerned with atheism , but rather with personal power or ' communism as opposed to atheism ' is what strikes me as dishonest and evasive , not the argument that atheism is less detrimental in general . Regarding the fallacy of division , I am not saying that Stalin did all the bad stuff he did for the sake of spreading atheism . No , he did not wake up and say , " hey , let's starve some Ukrainians today ... FOR ATHEISM ! " But the specific persecution of religious institutions and individuals was carried out to advance state atheism .

Basically , I've just got run of the mill depression , panic disorder , as well as sleep disturbances due to a very rare genetic condition I have called Ehlers-Danlos syndrome , which causes me extreme chronic pain , I have seen palliative care physicians , neurologists , physiatrists ( not the same as a psychiatrist ) , and pain management physicians ( anesthesiologists or physiatrists who have completed an extensive fellowship post residency in pain medicine ) , neurosurgeons , orthopedic surgeons , and of course a few internists , all of whom have confirmed the diagnosis . The level of pain I experience is what causes my depression for the most part ( though , I have developed thought patterns as a result of my pain which can trigger a depressive episode , I am working with my psychologist to learn coping skills and the like ) . Basically , the pain I have prevents me from doing several of my favorite things , things that you wouldn't even think would be influenced by pain , like simply going over to friends houses to sit around and play video games , walking up stairs , going to the store , but the most serious issue is the effect this disorder has had on my academic performance . The thing I've written this all for is to give you some understanding of the challenges I face in everyday life . It's not a raster . I think they typically use an MCP ( microchannel plate ) to amplify the signal , and I don't know what kind of CCD . The counts are measured in 2D , all at once . The way it works is you shoot some electrons at an area of the sample . The electrons are reflected or diffracted by the sample surface ( and the reflectivity depends on different surface features ) . You take these electrons and use electron optics to form a magnified image at the detector ( CCD or MCP ) . The intensity of electrons at the detector ( or brightness of the image ) is proportional to the reflectivity of the sample . So you're basically imaging the reflectivity of the sample at different positions . The reflectivity also varies as a function of the incident electron energy ( typically zero to a couple of tens of eV ) . When you image the sample , you try to use an electron energy where different features contrast the most . You can also do spectroscopy by measuring the reflectivity as a function of kinetic energy .
